attributes.magic: ELF 64-bit LSB executable, x86-64, version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, stripped

threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ids_results.rule_raw: alert ( gid:116; sid:58; rev:2; msg:"(tcp) experimental TCP options found"; metadata: policy max-detect-ips drop, rule-type decode; classtype:protocol-command-decode;)

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The binary is a backdoor/bot that performs extensive system reconnaissance and communicates with a Command and Control (C2) server. It daemonizes itself by forking, creating a new session, and redirecting I/O to `/dev/null`. It gathers information by enumerating processes and reading various files in `/proc`, such as `/proc/net/tcp`, `/proc/cpuinfo`, and `/proc/self/exe`. The malware exfiltrates this data to a C2 server, using the string "FrshPckBnnnSplit" as a likely cryptographic key. It exhibits aggressive behavior by killing processes, specifically targeting any process named "login" and any process older than a set duration (~8.7 days).
